Berchemia discolor

   [3697.jpg]
    Authority   Hemsl.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Rhamnales:Rhamnaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 3697

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: It is a shrub or tree reaching 3-20 m in height, with a
   straight bole, rough, dark grey bark that flakes longitudinally and a
   dense, rounded crown. USE: The fruit and seed are edible. The fruit has
   a high content of sugar and vitamin C. The fruit may be eaten boiled
   with sorghum. A beverage similar to tea is made from the leaves. The
   fruit and leaves can be used as fodder. The flowers are visited by
   bees. The wood is excellent for making furniture. The heartwood
   produces resin and dye. The roots have various medicinal uses. It is
   planted as an ornamental and is an effective shade tree and can also be
   used as a windbreak. GROWING PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: bird
   plum, dog plum, mountain date, wild almond. FURTHER INF: It grows
   naturally in various climates, from semi-arid areas to areas receiving
   rainfall in 4 years out of 5. It is found scattered in semi-desert
   grassland, open woodland or at lower altitudes along river valleys,
   especially on termite mounds. It is common in riverine forests,
   Acacia-Commiphora-Balanites woodland and wooded grassland, Acacia
   woodland and bushland, and the miombo woodlands of Tanzania. It
   tolerates drought but is not resistant to frost or cold wind.

   Sources
   SOURCE: ICRAF Agroforestree Database

